    {
      "id": "24a0d91958c4e9e7e4b9d9e43c54b52b8cd5e651",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2021-12-09 02:55:00.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nFun fact - with 720 sanity runs in the past week, est. 37k/year, every second that a sanity.sh test takes is about 10h for a test cluster of 4 or 5 VMs per year...\n\nHowever, each test *failure* is about 5h for the same cluster, so we need a subtest failure rate less than 1/19000 ~= 99.99% pass rate to make it worthwhile to save that second of testing.\n\nAlso, there are much better ways to globally optimize test time (e.g. faster mount/unmount, fewer reformats, speed up pool creation, etc) than worry about a few seconds in a single subtest.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
